frameDefinitions: An Agent causes a Speaker to become silent, sometimes about a particular Topic.
An Agent or Cause causes a Process or State to continue.
An Author creates a Text, either written, such as a letter, or spoken, such as a speech,  that contains meaningful linguistic tokens, and may have a particular Addressee in mind.
In this frame a Speaker ceases speaking, sometimes about a particular Topic.
This frame concerns people being in an altered mental state that is induced by an Intoxicant.
In this frame, a Communicator judges the Addressee and then communicates that appraisal directly to the Addressee.
frameExamples: The goaltenders <t>kept</t> the game going with terrific saves.
I <t>penned</t> a letter concerning racism to Congress.
Finally, Jan <t>shut</t> <t>up</t> about his car accident.
The principal <t>rebuked</t> the student for cheating on the exam.
listRoleDefinitions: The Agent is the person performing the intentional act.
The sentient entity that is not communicating.
The <fen>Expressor</fen> is the <fen>Speaker</fen>'s voice or other communicative noise emitted by the <fen>Speaker</fen>.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
The individual who causes the <fen>Process</fen> to continue or the <fen>State</fen> to be maintained.
A <fen>Process</fen> that is maintained by the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Cause</fen>.
The <fen>State</fen> that is maintained by the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Cause</fen>.
An event that causes the <fen>Process</fen> or <fen>State</fen> to be maintained.
The time at which the <fen>Process</fen> continues.
The location at which the <fen>Process</fen> continues.
The <fen>Author</fen> produces a particular <fen>Text</fen>.
The entity which results from the act of writing or speaking.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> at which the text is created.
Where the event takes place.
The <fen>Speaker</fen> has previously been speaking but has now stopped.
The <fen>Expressor</fen> is the <fen>Speaker</fen>'s voice or other communicative noise emitted by the <fen>Speaker</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the becoming silent occurs.
The <fen>Place</fen> is the location where the becoming silent occurs.
The mental state of the <fen>Cognizer</fen> is changed by an <fen>Intoxicant</fen> .
The <fen>Intoxicant</fen> alters the <fen>Cognizer</fen>'s mental experience.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Cognizer</fen> becomes intoxicated.
The <fen>Communicator</fen> communicates a judgment to the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The <fen>Addressee</fen> is jduged by the <fen>Communicator</fen> and receives the message of approval or disapproval.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the subject on which the <fen>Addressee</fen> is being judged.
The <fen>Reason</fen> is why the Communicator forms the type of judgment they form.
The <fen>Medium</fen> identifies the physical or abstract entity in which the judgment is conveyed.
An action or entity under the control of the <fen>Communicator</fen> that expresses the criticism or praise directed towards the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The point in time at which the <fen>Communicator</fen> berates or compliments the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The location where the <fen>Communicator</fen> admonishes the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
